\par }{This is the readme file for the winamp remote controller.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s2\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar\outlinelevel1\adjustright \b\i\f1\lang2057\cgrid {Overview:
\par }\pard\plain \widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang2057\cgrid {
\par Have you ever encountered one of these dire situations?
\par 
\par      Only one stereo, too many machines? 
\par      Can't... Raise... Bulk... - Must... Resist... Sofa... 
\par      I dream of the day I can put "written listening to winamp" on one of my products; 'til then, nobody must know I
\par      work with the stereo on... 
\par      We want to be able to share choosing the tracks on the winamp machine, but without playing musical chairs. 
\par 
\par Do you have Windows machines, networked via tcp-ip*?
\par 
\par * If not, why not?
\par 
\par If so, this may be the application suite for you!
\par 
\par And it's free!
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s2\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar\outlinelevel1\adjustright \b\i\f1\lang2057\cgrid {What it does: 
\par }\pard\plain \widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang2057\cgrid {
\par The broadest overview would have to be that the winamp plugin gives winamp the ability to respond to control
\par messages from remote machines connected via a network.
\par 
\par In more concrete terms - install the plugin, and you can control winamp on machine 1, by using a client application on
\par machine 2.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s2\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar\outlinelevel1\adjustright \b\i\f1\lang2057\cgrid {The Client 
\par }\pard\plain \widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang2057\cgrid {
\par Installation:
\par 
\par Simply use one of the setup options in the setup provided.
\par 
\par Use:
\par 
\par Simply get the endpoint right (machine, endpoint - read it off the server messages form), and it should just work
\par 
\par I hope the interface is fairly self-explanatory - just try it out!
\par 
\par ps - right click the tray-icon for a menu, and left click for a quick pause, when the back manager calls.
\par The pause code actually tests to see if the server state is consistent with what you are seeing, and does not act if winamp
\par is already paused.
\par So you can *all* dive for pause at once (ish).
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s2\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar\outlinelevel1\adjustright \b\i\f1\lang2057\cgrid {The Server 
\par }\pard\plain \widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang2057\cgrid {
\par Installation:
\par 
\par Simply use the "Typical" setup or "Custom" and select the server plugin group.
\par 
\par The server plugin install option puts a shortcut to install the winamp plugin. Click on this while winamp is not running,
\par and restart winamp - the plugin is loaded automatically by winamp at startup, and it starts to export winamp's abilities
\par soon after, assuming all is well with your machine.
\par 
\par Use:
\par 
\par "Out of the box", this will work straight off for client, server and winamp all on the same machine.
\par 
\par To finally use the suite as intended, you will have to have a client remote to the winamp machine, that can "see" the
\par server endpoint.
\par 
\par New - now the locate servers function will find the local winamp server for you!
\par 
\par *Users without a network, or only dial-up read me 
\par - Without a known IP address, these calls, and the remote's operation can take a very long time.
\par In these cases, I recommend adding the line 
\par 
\par 127.0.0.1 localhost # this is the local loopback
\par 
\par to the Windows Hosts file.
\par What's the windows hosts file?
\par Well, in the Windows directory, or WinNT/System32/drivers/etc, there should be a file called (just) 
\par 
\par HOSTS
\par 
\par which contains a list of ip address lookups - win9x often has a hosts.sam sample file.
\par With the previous line added, the ip alias localhost is available as the local loopback address.
\par You could even add your machine name (try to resist the temptation to make it www.microsoft.com - it will "override"
\par real net aliases, and prevent you going there.)
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s2\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar\outlinelevel1\adjustright \b\i\f1\lang2057\cgrid {What You will need: 
\par }\pard\plain \widctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang2057\cgrid {
\par      The Installation process 
\par      Get the install files 
\par      Run setup 
\par      Select Your option
\par      - Typical gives you the server and the client.
\par      - Compact gives you client only.
\par      - Custom gives you option to select the client, server and MS OpenGL options. 
\par      Continue with the setup - to install the server, click on the "install server plugin" link 
\par      You are now ready to go - the client needs only the correct endpoint setting - the default should be OK.
\par      If you have trouble and the server is definitely running on a machine you can 'see', have a work with your network
\par      person, if you have one.
\par      If all else fails, drop me a line, maybe it's my fault, or I can help. 
\par 
